context: The formation of the party was formally announced at <a0_0><b4_0>Sydney Town Hall<b4_0/><a0_0/> on 31 August 1945. It took the name "Liberal" <a1_0><b5_0>in honour of the old Commonwealth Liberal Party<b5_0/><a1_0/>. The new party was dominated by the remains of the old UAP; with few exceptions, the UAP party room became the Liberal party room. <b8_0>The Australian Women's National League<b8_0/>, a powerful conservative women's organisation, also merged with the new party. A conservative youth group Menzies had set up, the Young Nationalists, was also merged into the new party. It became the nucleus of the Liberal Party's youth division, the <a2_0><b6_0>Young Liberals<b6_0/><a2_0/>. By September 1945 there were <a3_0><b7_0>more than 90,000<b7_0/><a3_0/> members, many of whom had not previously been members of any political party.
